AVIAN INFLUENZA (172): UK (ENGLAND), TURKEYS
********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Thu 15 Nov 2007
Source: The Telegraph [edited]
<http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/11/15/nflu415.xml>


The bird flu crisis escalated today [15 Nov 2007] as vets said the
virus may have spread to a 2nd farm a few kilometers from the initial
outbreak. Turkeys at Grove Farm near Botesdale in Suffolk were being
slaughtered on suspicion of having the disease.

The site is within a 3 km (2 mi) protection zone established around
Redgrave Park Farm where the deadly H5N1 virus was 1st discovered on
Sunday [11 Nov 2007].

A precautionary cull had already been ordered at Grove Farm because
it is owned by the same firm as Redgrave Park Farm but when animal
health officials turned up they found a number of birds deed.

The 2 farms and 3 others also run by Redgrave Poultry are all staffed
by the same 5 workers and vets believe they or their vehicles could
have transferred the virus.

In all nearly 30 000 turkeys are being gassed at the 5 farms.

Vets have yet to establish how the virus arrived in Suffolk. It is
the same strain that caused outbreaks in Germany and Bohemia this
summer [2007] and one theory is that it was brought by migrating
birds, which settled on an ornamental lake near Redgrave Park Farm.

A Redgrave Poultry spokesman denied suggestions that the disease
could have come from imported ducklings from the Netherlands. Young
ducks, turkeys and geese at all 5 farms, and all their feed, were
sourced from the UK, he said. The Dutch farm ministry said only one
consignment of ducklings had gone recently to the UK and the delivery
was 50 km (31 mi) away from where the outbreak occurred.

Another line of inquiry is that Gressingham Foods, of which Redgrave
Poultry is a subsidiary, also imports specialist meats like Barbary
duck and poussin [spring chicken or Cornish game hen], which are
processed at a plant less than a kilometre (0.6 mi) from the scene of
the outbreak.

The possible spread of the disease to another farm was a bitter blow
to the GBP 3.4 billion (approx. USD 7 billion) poultry industry and
there were warnings that supply shortages could mean consumers have
to pay more than GBP 100 (USD 206) for an organic Christmas turkey.

A total of 1200 poultry producers, with 25 million birds -- including
2 million turkeys -- lie inside a restricted zone imposed on the
whole of Suffolk and most of Norfolk and are barred from moving their
flocks outside it.

Within 10 km (6 mi) of the outbreak, there are 89 producers who have
had to isolate 4 million birds. The restrictions on them will only be
lifted 30 days after the outbreak is declared over, meaning the birds
may not make it to stores in time for Christmas.

Investigators are looking at disinfectant procedures on the 5
Redgrave Poultry farms and also trying to establish if people or
vehicles from there travelled to other parts of the UK. "If there is
evidence of a movement elsewhere in the country we will have to take
precautions," a source said.

Jeremy Blackburn, a spokesman for the British Poultry Council, urged
the public to back British turkey. "At the moment we haven't seen a
noticeable drop in sales," he said.

The other 3 farms involved are Stone House Farm in West Harling,
Norfolk, Bridge Farm in Pulham, Norfolk, and Hill Meadow in
Knettishall, Suffolk.

[Byline: Nick Allen]

